{{User:JakitoFan/Class Custom/4|class=5|hexagon=5|header=Threat Index - Class|safety=Unsafe|security=Insecure|entity=Severe Environmental Threats|environment=|bg-image=Stormyhallways.gif|bg-size=1500px|text-color=ffffff|chevron=>}}'''Level 266''', known colloquially as the Stormy Hallways, is the 267<sup>th</sup> level of the Backrooms.

==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=Stormyhallways.gif|caption=A snippet of a captured recording of '''Level 266'''. Photographer deceased.|hovertext=BRICK BY BRICK}}{{Blurimage|file=Untitled design (22).gif|caption=A tighter corridor within '''Level 266'''. Photographer alive.|hovertext=TUNNELS OF PLENTY}}'''Level 266''' manifests generally as a presumably infinite network of interconnected mostly brick hallways. Subtle details, like color and condition, tend to vary in appearance depending on the wanderer who enters. These network of hallways are consistently brick, although certain areas may have stylistically deviant areas such as futuristic spaceship-esque corridors reminiscent of Level 15 or the balcony of a large castle. While most areas are indoors, certain stylistically deviant areas and even typical hallways may have wide open ceilings, revealing a raging storm. Although a downpour of rain is consistent the floors are always dry; the water evaporates due to unknown causes before interacting with the floor, and instead only stays stuck onto the wanderer. The cause of the fluctuating environments for '''Level 266''' are yet to be determined, though it is generally hypothesized that individual wanderers within the level perceive different areas, identical in shape but varying in details.

'''Level 266''' is nigh impossible to reside in due to the constant presence of the storm. Winds produced by this storm have been recorded to reach up to 250 miles per hour, although the wind speeds are usually around 20 miles an hour, and regularly fluctuate to around 70 miles per hour. The higher wind speeds are sufficient to knock a wanderer off balance and potentially send them flying into walls, which is a great environmental danger. The wind speeds are most prevalent in more stylistically deviant areas, as open gaps allow the wind to enter far easier. These areas are also where the highest wind speeds are recorded. Notably, various parts of the network of tunnels are sealed off by heavy metal doors. At first glance they are impassable, but further investigation has led to the interesting conclusion that these doors are intangible for humans, but prevent the wind from entering. These are efficient safe zones for wanderers.

The level's never-ending storm may also produce large flashes of lightning, which cause damage to bricks in and out of these safe zones. Wind does not enter through gaps created by this method, but rain still does, so it is advised to avoid them still. The lightning never breaches to the interior of the tunnel. While the level does have similarities to other levels with similar layouts such as [[Level 3]] and [[Level 34]], there are several environmental differences. The level is typically shrouded in darkness, with lighting coming from glowing balls of light latched on to the wall through anomalous means and the lightning strikes from above. The balls of light are incredibly hot to the touch, so one should never attempt to interact with them. Notably, certain rooms separated from the level's corridors are present, accessible via small fire exit doors. These rooms are made of weathered brick and usually contain tables and chairs strewn around, with meager supplies found in boxes around the area. However, the boxes' supplies automatically regenerate on a thirty-hour cycle, which can only be interrupted by searching the box during an interval of 30 hours. These supplies are insufficient to support more than one person at any time, and they are few and far between, making sustained human inhabitation technically possible but a logistical nightmare.

==Phenomena==

Two notable phenomena are associated with '''Level 266'''.

===Flicker===
<span style="font-size:5px">Not to be confused with [[Phenomenon 12|The Flicker]], a Backrooms-wide catastrophic event.<br>
</span>The Flicker event occurs randomly, on average every 20 hours. During this phenomenon, the floating lights present in the level shut off, bathing the level in darkness, with the only illumination being the occasional flash of lightning. During this time, the resident entity activity reaches an all time low, as if this was a dedicated period of rest. However, wind speeds do increase to an average of 50mph and a high of 100mph, enough to blow a wanderer off their feet. Take extreme caution during this period. During this time, the regenerating boxes of supplies no longer provide anything. The phenomenon lasts exactly five hours, and upon its conclusion entity activity will resume, wind speeds will drop and the glowing balls of light will return.
===The Great Gust===
The Great Gust occurs on a set schedule, happening once for the New Moon and once for the Full Moon. During this period of time, wind speeds rise sharply, achieving speeds of up to 400 miles per hour. This causes mass destruction, disassembling parts of the tunnel and blowing wanderers into the void that lies below. This does not affect stylistically deviant corridors made of strong enough material such as strong alloys, or accepted safe zones. Instead, these areas see a dramatic decrease in wind speed, slowly reaching 0mph as the air becomes completely stagnant. During this time, entity activity reaches a full stop, but sees a brief resurgence after 30 minutes, which is about when the phenomenon ends. After this resurgence, activity will resume at its normal pace.

==Entities==

The primary entities present within the level are [[Entity 4|Deathmoths]], crowding around the light and in large numbers. [[Entity 5|Clumps]] and [[Entity 112|The Armless]] are also present, and rarely, [[Entity 455|Felix]] can be located in safe zones.

==Colonies and Outposts==
While there is a small nomadic human population, self-identifying as the '''Wind Resistants''', no official colonies or outposts can be established due to the level's turbulent environment.

==Level History==
The level was initially discovered by Catherine Nguyen of the [[M.E.G.|Major Explorer Group]], who had no-clipped in from [[Level 302]], on May 12th, 1993. This level was given the provisional designation of Level '''34.2''', due to perceived similarities in the level's structure with [[Level 34]]. Eventually, the level was reclassified as ''''''Level 34.5'''''<nowiki />' on March 1st, 1994, due to later discovered differences between other levels and this one. Upon the obsolescence of the Negative Levels category, the level was moved to a positive slot under ''''''Level 266'''''', a name which the level holds today. Entities in the form of [[Entity 5|Clumps]] were discovered in September of 1996, with the full catalog of the level's entity presence being discovered later that year. On June 19th, 2001, a hidden staircase in Room 1457 of the [[Level 399#Description 2|Rosatin Hotel]] was discovered to lead into this level, and later locked away by a private owner until late 2022. By 2005, all entrances and exits in relation to this level were fully documented. During October 15th of 2022, the level suddenly disappeared off the radar, with entrances no longer functioning and its [[The Database|database]] article deleted. Sometime during March 2025, however, the level resurfaced fully, with only minor structural alterations and an exit to [[The Void]] and [[Level 901|VO-004]].

==Entrances and Exits==
===Entrances===
*Stylistically deviant areas of [[Level 3]] may lead into the main structure.
*Levels primarily comprising of a corridor layout may segue into this level.
*Loading a rare .exe file labeled 'CHICAGOTUNNELS' on the [[Entity PC]] may lead here.
*Noclipping into bricks strewn around certain levels may lead here.
*In Room 1457 of the [[Level 399#Description 2|Rosatin Hotel]], a staircase hewn from brick headed down is present, descending may lead here.
===Exits===
*Rarely, staircases upward may appear, ascending them leads to [[Level 267]].
*Stylistically deviant hallways resembling other levels may segue to the level they mimic.
**However, ascending a staircase with the word 'MAIN FLOOR' will lead to the [[Level 399#Description 2|Rosatin Hotel]], Room 1457.
*Falling into the level's void will send one to [[The Void|the Void]], or rarely [[Level 901|VO-004]].
*Attempting to manually break the level's walls will send one to [[Level 5.55]].
*Falling asleep within the level has a low chance to bring one to [[Level 365]].
*A dark hallway will lead one [[Level 959|there]], particularly to its second floor.
